I don't think you need to consider the internal body anatomy. Much of the art style in the listed examples relies on the fact that the style itself is a very abstract representation of, say, the waddle dee. As it's never really been expanded upon by HAL laboratories, this exercise is left to the player. Given the NES's restrictions, a lot of the graphics are abstract like this. <br /><br />However, this is maybe the closest example you're going to find in the real world: <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ykuXGdukBZA" class="postlink">Pygmy jerboa</a><p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=5314">mikejmoffitt</a> — Sun Dec 21, 2014 8:49 pm</p><hr />
